Elwha River Dam Removal - Chinook Salmon (Oncorhynchus tshawytscha) Recovery Analysis using Python

Introduction

The Elwha River Dam Removal project serves as a novel case study for river restoration following the removal of large-scale dams. Understanding the impacts of dam removal and the nuances of the changes that follow are crucial for future restoration projects. The Elwha dam was nearly 100 years old when it was removed. The Elwha River Dam was originally completed in 1913 to supply energy to a pulp mill for the regions booming logging industry. Driven by demand, the Glines Canyon Dam, about 8 miles upstream, followed in 1927 (NPS, 2025). This marked the beginning of what would soon become a national trend. From the 1930s to the 1970s, the United States experienced a dramatic increase in dam building, sometimes referred to as The Big Dam Era (Lee, 2023), for benefits such as hydropower, flood control, irrigation, and water supply.

However, later in the 20th century, research began to understand the unforeseen consequences dams often had, such as habitat loss, habitat fragmentation, impacts on fish, reduced sediment transport, and social impacts like displaced communities or livelihoods. The Elwha River was once a thriving salmon habitat with plentiful fish, but dams alter fish migration due to changes in sediment load, hydrologic flow, and changes in water quality, such as temperature, nutrients, and oxygen (U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, 2021). It is estimated that before dam removal, the salmon habitat was reduced by 90% of pre-dam availability due to blocked migration routes. Historical estimates place salmon abundance at around 380,000 to 500,000 annual returns on the Elwha River, whereas a study conducted between 1990 - 2000 found an average of 5,500 salmon annual returns (Pess et al., 2008). This shows a declining trend in salmon in the region since the implementation of the dam. This includes Chinook salmon, a keystone species for the health and stability of the entire ecosystem.

In recent decades, with growing evidence, dam removal is occurring more often in an attempt to restore riparian habitat, natural hydrologic flow, and sediment transport. The dams on the Elwha River became an issue of environmental justice as well, and the Lower Elwha Kallum Tribe was a primary advocate in the push for dam removal. Salmon are a significant part of the lives of the Lower Elwha Klallum people for cultural, spiritual, and physical purposes (Guarino, 2013). After lobbying with additional environmental groups, Congress passed the Elwha River Ecosystem and Fisheries Restoration Act in 1992, and the federal government later purchased the dams. The dam removal process wasnt completed fully until 2014 (NPS, 2025).

Multiple salmon species, such as the Coho, and trout species, such as Steelhead, are important fish species to the region and to research in the Elwha River restoration project. This data analysis analyzed Chinook salmon recovery specifically due to their cultural significance, keystone species status, ecological importance, and their sensitivity to changes in water quality.

Study Area

The Elwha River is 45 miles originating in the Olympic Mountains in Washington, U.S., on the Olympic Peninsula, flowing north to the Strait of Juan De Fuca. There were two dams along the Elwha River that were removed. The Elwha Dam removal was completed in 2012, and Glines Canyon Dam was fully removed in 2014. This dam removal project was a huge undertaking, and it was the largest in history at the time. It is estimated to have reopened 75 miles of salmon habitat (U.S.NOAA Fisheries, 2025).

Methods

This data analysis acquired USGS data from the National Hydrography Dataset (NHD) to retrieve the Watershed Boundary Dataset (WBD) for the Elwha-Dungeness Watershed (HUC8-17110020) at the subbasin level. The polygon was further refined via geospatial processing to just the Elwha watershed data (HUC12) from the entire subbasin polygon. An interactive plot of the Elwha watershed boundary and the defined study area was created. Additionally, the project was originally going to use Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF) data but there were not enough documented occurrences before and after the dam removals in the watershed boundary to get a clear picture of Chinook salmon recovery. A salmonid snorkeling survey dataset was available from USGS snorkeling surveys conducted in 2007/2008 before the dam removal and 2018/2019 after the dam removal. The USGS salmonid CSV file was downloaded and converted into a pandas dataframe. The columns and dataset were inspected, species codes were verified through the metadata file, and filtered to the species of interest, Chinook (Count_Onts, Fish_km_Onts). The dataset was aggregated by year, count, and density. The river reach data was combined per year for the sum of the total counts of Chinook, and the mean density was calculated across all river reaches. Individual river reach survey data could not be plotted individually due to a lack of consistent coordinate data for the river reaches. The total abundance each year and mean density were plotted on bar and scatter plots, respectively. The Chinook counts and mean density per year were added to the dissolved Elwha watershed polygon. This created a geodataframe with one polygon per year, which was then visualized as an interactive map using hvPlot to show changes before and after the dam removal.

Data Citations

USGS. (2021). Riverscape snorkeling surveys of salmonid distribution and abundance before (2007, 2008) and after (2018, 2019) dam removal on the Elwha River, Washington [Dataset]. USGS Science Data Catalog

U.S.Geological Survey. Watershed Boundary Dataset (WBD), 8digit Hydrologic Unit Code 17110020 DungenessElwha. National Geospatial Technical Operations Center, 2025.

# Aggregate total counts and mean density per year
chinook_year_summary = chinook_year_df.groupby('Year', as_index=False).agg({
    'Chinook_count': 'sum',       # sum the counts (abundance)
    'Chinook_per_km': 'mean'      # take mean of density
})

### Due to holoview identifying the same polygon in geodataframe, a function was created
### Selects new polygon each time slider moves
# Load panel extension 
pn.extension('plotly') 

# Precompute min/max for consistent color scale and hover
vmin = salmon_elwha_watershed_gdf['Chinook_per_km'].min()
vmax = salmon_elwha_watershed_gdf['Chinook_per_km'].max()

# Create a discrete slider widget for year
year_widget = pn.widgets.DiscreteSlider(
    name='Year',
    options=sorted(salmon_elwha_watershed_gdf['Year'].unique()),
    width=700
)

# Define the plotting function for a single year **Created with help of ChatGPT**
def plot_year(year):
    df = salmon_elwha_watershed_gdf[salmon_elwha_watershed_gdf['Year'] == year].copy()
    return df.hvplot(
        geo=True,
        tiles='EsriImagery',
        color='Chinook_per_km',
        line_width=5,
        hover_cols=['Year', 'Chinook_count', 'Chinook_per_km'],
        frame_width=700,
        frame_height=500,
        title='Elwha River Chinook Salmon Recovery (Before/After Dam Removal 2012-2014)',
        clim=(vmin, vmax),            # consistent color scale & hover details
        hover_line_color='white',      
        hover_line_width=3
    )

# Bind the slider to the plotting function
chinook_year_map2 = pn.bind(plot_year, year=year_widget)

# Create layout with plot on top and slider at bottom
pn.Column(
    chinook_year_map2,
    year_widget
)

Return of the King: Chinook Salmon Recovery in the Elwha River Watershed following Dam Removals in 2012 - 2014

Chinook salmon are back and King of the Elwha River once again! In this data analysis using Python, geospatial analysis, and actual snorkeling survey data from USGS, I analyzed the Chinooks return following a large-scale dam removal. An increase in the total count of Chinook salmon (abundance) over time was observed from the pre-dam removal surveys in 2007/2008 to the post-dam removal surveys in 2018/2019. This could indicate the beginning of a population-scale recovery, and the counts are increasing only a few years after dam removal. This is a positive sign that Chinook salmon are making a return to their former extensive habitat.

An increase in the density of Chinook salmon (per km) was also observed, and the mean density calculated across all river reaches showed a dramatic increase. This indicates the use of the entire habitat surveyed, including areas upstream previously blocked off by the dam. The survey reported that higher densities were seen in previously inaccessible parts of the river, at higher densities than even seen downstream from the dam prior to removal (Torgersen et al., 2021). To clean and visualize these changes, I used data analysis tools such as pandas, geopandas, and hvplot libraries.

Chinook are a keystone species and important food source for both marine and terrestrial apex predators, which in turn impact the entire health and stability of the ecosystem. Chinook are important for nutrient cycling throughout their life cycle. A large amount of wood and sediment was trapped upstream from the dam, and following the dam removal, was released. This release reshaped the riverbed and created new habitat. Sediments are important for salmon breeding; this release likely had an initial disruption on the existing populations downstream, which quickly rebounded (NOAA, 2024). This sediment redistribution also helps with vegetation regrowth.

Indigenous people (Lower Elwha Klallam Tribe) advocated intensely for this dam removal. Chinook salmon are very important culturally, spiritually, and physically, so this salmon recovery has a broader impact socially and economically, not just ecologically (Guarino, 2013). The Chinook recovery improves food security and cultural survival for the tribe.

Some limitations of this analysis included that the coordinate data for individual river reaches were not available, and the snorkeling survey only had four sample events, two years before the dam removal and two years after. There are a lot of possibilities for future analysis to plot the individual counts/densities for each river reach if the proper coordinates for the river reaches were available, which could then be analyzed spatially. Also, plotting a comparison of other salmon and trout species that are vital to a successful restoration project could be valuable. It would also be interesting to plot this salmon recovery alongside water quality, water temperature, or other hydrologic data to compare the increase with those parameters as well.

Overall, the Chinook salmon recovery is not only a story of habitat restoration but also of environmental justice and tribal sovereignty. While benefits from dams like hydropower and flood control are valuable, the impacts on larger ecosystem cycles are too great to be ignored. This data analysis displayed an increase in an important keystone species, the Chinook salmon. Rewilding rivers through dam removal is an important tool in riparian conservation, restoration, and preservation.
